Japan, 2000<br>
Directed by: Kazuya Tsurumaki<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;I can't tell where the truth ends and the lies begin&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - Naota<br>
<br>
What is FLCL? Apparently no one knows for sure. Naota's grandpa suggests that it's all in the hands - furi kuri, furi kura... His father claims it has something to do with &quot;that type of relationship&quot;. Haruko... well Haruko's never any help.<br>
<br>
Nothing ever happens in Naota's sleepy town, that is until he gets hit over the head with a bass guitar and a rather large horn starts growing out of his head. The horn in question turns out to be the finger of a giant robotic hand which escapes Naota's forehead alongside a strange TV-headed robot.<br>
<br>
I guess a town housing a factory shaped like a gigantic clothes iron can't be that ordinary after all...<br>
<br>
Still with me?<br>
<br>
Perhaps the best way to summarize FLCL is to simply say that it is a disjointed, bizarre and incredibly brillant coming of age story featuring all the regular &quot;anime standards&quot; but, as always, with a Gainax twist.<br>
<br>
Nothing is ever as it seems, not when Gainax is involved. Things don't work quite the way they should, characters act in unpredictable (yet sometimes eerily realistic) fashion while the viewer is bombarded with rapid fire imagery that borders on the surrealist.<br>
<br>
Somewhere in there, nestled in between unusual giant robots and countless self-references, is a fascinating character study about a young boy in an average, boring city facing ever so common but still bothersome situations.<br>
<br>
For example, Naota's brother is off to America to play baseball and so he must endure repeated comparisons to his departed kin from the local baseball team coached by his grandfather. His brother's girlfriend keeps flirting with the boy, going as far as nibbling on his ear in an attempt at replacing her now distant lover. But Naota doesn't like sour stuff - or spicy stuff for that matter - sweet is the way to go. Is this right? Is this how Naota should behave?<br>
<br>
In FLCL, people are selfish and this includes Naota who, at one point, expects Mamimi (his brother's girlfriend) to understand that being around Haruko should not stop her from showering him with attention. He doesn't care much for her brand of affection in the early going, but being left without it he soon changes his tune.<br>
<br>
While Gainax offers some answers, they leave the door open for further discussion - this might be the right way, but they aren't really sure.<br>
<br>
FLCL represents one of the first &quot;post-Anno&quot; (Anno as in quasi-legendary and controversial anime director Hideaki Anno) anime from Gainax. It would make sense then that Gainax chose a team comprised of Anno understudies as well as individuals who worked on such projects as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Shin Seiki Evangelion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Kareshi Kanojou no Jijou</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Martian Successor Nadesico</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>La Fillette Révolutionnaire Utena</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - all of which have gained some notoriety amongst the more intellectual fans of anime/manga.<br>
<br>
If anything it has the feel and style of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Kareshi Kanojou no Jijou</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>His and Her Circumstances</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->), Anno's last contribution to the Gainax studios: from manga pages replacing the animation to the constant stream of self-references to the unique and rather oddball character design/animation. I should note that they go one step further by introducing references to The Matrix AND, of all things, South Park (those scenes received tremendous reactions from the crowd).<br>
<br>
Also, FLCL follows a similar theme as that of other Gainax &quot;hits&quot; like Kare Kano, Top o Nare! Gunbuster and Evangelion. In fact, one might say that the leitmotiv of all these productions is the awkwardness and ambivalence of maturity - just what does it mean to be &quot;mature&quot; and how (and when, if not why) should we attempt to reach this &quot;maturity&quot;?<br>
<br>
Gainax has been (not so) secretely toying around with this idea for ages now and even non-Anno productions feature this focus on the difficult passage to adulthood - if such a thing really exists. However, the real targets here are the anime/manga otaku - the obsessive fans whose very lives depend on the anime/manga they love - for the folks at Gainax were (and probably still are) otaku themselves. After all, the otaku is sometimes understood as an adult-child phenomenon - an individual who plays with toys and watches cartoons while holding down a job to pay for his expensive hobbies.<br>
<br>
Gainax has tried reaching out to otaku in the past with limited success and in the case of Anno it led him to bitchslap all of otakudom with the very negative portrayal of Shinji in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The End of Evangelion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Despite their past failure to communicate their message, they persevere and FLCL is yet another attempt which I fear may have failed.<br>
<br>
Because of this non-anime/manga may find themselves completely lost at times. Some of the jokes and references are so obscure that I can't help but feel at least a little shame in the fact that I caught so many of them. Still, the booming soundtrack by The Pillows (a Japanese indie rock group) along with the utter weirdness of this anime make it a must see for anyone interested in the more experimental side of this often misunderstood world. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33001A><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bescape96855.showUserPublicProfile?gid=asplagis>Asplagis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>vagabond</span><br>  Posts: 197<br> <font color=#ff6663>(7/28/03 9:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=175.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fantasia 2003 - Reviews</span><hr size=1> I just reviewed Fantasia's showing of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Phone</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in the horror movie review thread in Transylvania. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#330000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bescape96855.showUserPublicProfile?gid=asplagis>Asplagis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>vagabond</span><br>  Posts: 202<br> <font color=#ff6663>(8/2/03 10:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=175.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fantasia 2003 - Reviews</span><hr size=1> Unless Hypnotic and Big Slaughter Club are considered a horror movies, all other reviews can be found in the Transylvania forum under the horror film review topic.<br>
