Mexico, 2001<br>
Directed by: Hector Molinar<br>
<br>
The original El Santo was arguably the single greatest technicos (the good guys in lucha libre) to grace a Mexican ring - despite what Mil Mascaras would have you think. His popularity in the 50's led to a long tradition of movies in which our burly, barrel chested luchadore would solve crime and combat various supernatural terrors including, in one case, ol' Count Dracula himself (then again, so did Billy the Kid)!<br>
<br>
Outside of Mexico few if any know of El Santo and his pro wrestling career let alone his numerous feature films. The lack of interest in lucha libre amongst U.S./Canadian fans along with that of American performers/promoters made it hard for a man like Santo to make an impact up north. His fellow technicos, Mil Mascaras, often appeared as a special attraction in the U.S. allowing him greater exposure but his own movie career was all but completely ignored up north.<br>
<br>
Of course the fact that these pictures probably seemed like strange experimental cinema to most movie goers didn't help. A typical lucha libre movie features at least a few matches which have little to no relevance to the plot of the movie itself, plus, the main star is wearing a pro wrestling mask the whole time. Obviously his unusual movies became the object of cult fandom all over the world.<br>
<br>
Alas, all good things must come to an end as the masked legend died in '84, leaving behind a legacy that his son - El Hijo del Santo - would quickly revive by putting on the trademark silver mask and cape. As a matter of fact, these events were documented in a movie featuring the fabled Son of Santo. In this movie El Hijo del Santo is portrayed as somehat insecure and ambivalent - those are some big shoes he has to fill and he isn't sure he can do it. Art doesn't always imitate life very well seeing as Santo made it clear that his son would persue his legacy and groomed him for his role very early on. <br>
<br>
However, unlike his legendary father, El Hijo Del Santo doesn't have nearly as many movies under his belt. Thus, Infraterrestre is an attempt by the son of Santo to bring back the old tradition of Santo movies to a new generation and perhaps even outside of Mexico.<br>
<br>
In this CGI-laden affair, a number of odd disappearances occur all over Mexico with only one actual witness - a young boy named Diego who has been rendered mute due to the events he saw. The police are left with quite a caper on their hands so when things get this bad, they call upon the Earth's greatest luchadore - El Santo!<br>
<br>
As always in lucha libre movie logic only a masked Mexican wrestler can hope to save us from impending doom.<br>
<br>
But Santo is always one step ahead of everyone and already begun his own investigation regarding some disturbing and possibly related events. During a match with a formidable masked rudo opponent (the bad guys in lucha libre) called Blue Panther, the aforementioned rudo suddenly becomes particularly violent and dastardly; he refuses to break a choke, pushes the referee around and uses other unethical tactics to wear down the man in the silve mask. The mysterious rudo also manages to shift his centre of gravity at will in order to escape Santo's mightiest moves without a single scratch! Eventually the match is stopped due to the interference of a group of musclebound thugs in black.<br>
<br>
Such violence and cruelty will justice prevail?<br>
<br>
The police decide to call in a child psychiatrist to see if she can reach out to Diego; perhaps her intervention will help them gather a few leads in this puzzling case. The lovely Doctor Alma Monreal (bwahahahahahahahahaha!!!) doesn't seem to like the Commander - or the rest of the police force fpr that matter. In a severe tone (well, as severe as the poor actress could manage) she blames them for Diego's silence. She stresses that the police are treating the poor child like an adult and that Diego needs time to recover.<br>
<br>
Enter the man in the silver mask. <br>
<br>
The boy finds his voice again as soon as he sees El Santo. Our big hearted luchadore hero calmly explains that no one asked Diego's permission before pelting him with questions and so the boy felt no need to respond.<br>
<br>
They find out that aliens took Diego's parents. The police regard this information as false but both the Doctor and Santo agree that it may be the lead they were looking for.<br>
<br>
The aliens eventually kidnap young Diego despite the <br>
police's(with Santo of course) timely intervention which sets up a crazy chase scene involving our masked hero's flying BMW and very own private satellite network. Seems the son put his inheritance money to good use!<br>
<br>
By way of his multi-purpose watch Santo determines that the aliens are underground - in Mexico's futuristic and particularly clean sewers. Having donned his cape and wrestling gear, Santo is prepared to face off with these evil invaders.<br>
<br>
Will Santo find Diego and unravel the mystery of these alien invaders?<br>
<br>
Of course he will! It's an El Santo movie for pete's sake!<br>
<br>
With ample CGI and cheap but plentiful special effects, this movie bears but a passing ressemblance to the Santo movies of old. In many ways this movie is closer to an American action series à la Xena or Hercules than one of those classic lucha libre meets drive-in classics. In my opinion this is a very bad mistake.<br>
<br>
First, the market for these is already flooded as it is - we don't need Mexico to tip over this vase. Second, the old Santo movies tried to hide their cheapness by using less SFX, relying instead on the actors' seriousness in the face of ridiculous and over the top situations.<br>
<br>
Most critics agree that Infraterrestre lacks the charm of the originals. Oh, there's no doubt that El Hijo del Santo is every bit the charismatic man his father was (not to mention a sharp dresser), however the movie itself was a tad too exagerated for my tastes at times. I mean, did Santo really need a flying BMW and his own satellite?<br>
<br>
Infraterrestre isn't without its moments and it blows away a lot of similar movies being made for American television. From Santo's macho dialogue and cheesy romance with the Doctor to the Terminator-like villains, there are moments when you can't help but enjoy yourself. I just loved the way he mad sure to put his cape back on after his battle with Blue Panther.<br>
<br>
Also, being in a theatre with a bunch of fellow Santo fans is  a far different experience than sitting at home with the DVD player as the sole witness to your reactions. Everyone there cheered for Santo while jeering Blue Panther's rudo ways. I myself was tempted to re-enact an old scene from a Santo match in which a spectator got up from his seat and had to be restrained by the others to avoid an altercation. Unfortunately me and my friends were too high and no one could see us.<br>
<br>
The staff encouraged us to show our support for Santo by cheering and chanting his name as loudly as possible - which we certainly did. In fact, they even gave us a couple of cheesy little acts before the picture. <br>
<br>
First we had the mask contest featuring a bunch of indy ECW wannabes from Montréal. One Hulk Hogan sound-alike came in with a green suit and mask, but the winner was some fellow with a weird black plastic mask that looked like a modified version of the original mask worn by puroresu sensation Jushin Liger.<br>
<br>
Afterwards we were treated to some hefty fellow in an El Santo mask fighting off an unnamed masked rudo(!!). The rudo in question was a complete ass - I mean he dared to pull off the fake Santo's mask! I'm as shocked as you are folks. But, thanks to the cheers of the audience, Santo made a surprise come back! You see, the crafty luchadore had another mask hidden underneath the first one. What a brillant tactic!<br>
<br>
With our help, he was able to deliver the final blow to his opponent - much to our delight of course.<br>
<br>
*sniff* It was a beautiful scene.<br>
<br>
Silliness aside, this Santo 2K1 just isn't up to the standards of the originals. A neophyte would do well to seek out some of the older pictures before watching this one, otherwise he might fail to appreciate what Infraterrestre and the Santo legacy have to offer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.showPrevMessage?topicID=175.topic"> <img src="http://myweb.thump.net/649222/esc/fleurprev.gif" border=0></a><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.showNextMessage?topicID=175.topic"> <img src="http://myweb.thump.net/649222/esc/fleurnext.gif" border=0> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=175.topic&index=10><img src=http://myweb.thump.net/649222/esc/aaddreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.threadControl?topicID=175.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=175.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fescape96855frm11.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=175.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub98.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=p